<page_title>Nematic phase liquid crystals</page_title>
<text>Nematic Phase Liquid Crystals

    
Liquid crystals are materials that are composed of rigid rod-like or disc-like molecules (mesogens[2]) that have strong dipoles and/or are easily polarizable by substitution. According to the PLC Virtual Textbook made by Case Western Reserve University, the distinguishing characteristic of liquid crystals is &quot;the tendency of the mesogens to point along a common axis, called the director&quot;. This is &quot;in contrast to molecules in the liquid phase, which have no intrinsic order&quot;, and to the solid state, in which molecules are &quot;highly ordered and have little translational freedom&quot;.</text>
